ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-1 The airplane was in cruise flight at 29,000 feet in smooth air with the seat belt sign turned off. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-2 The crew reported two jolts, and the airplane descended 600 feet. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-3 Due to possible injuries, the crew diverted to Bermuda (BDA) and landed. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-4 Readout of the flight data recorder indicated cruise flight at 29,000 feet with no change in heading, airspeed, or altitude for several minutes approaching the accident sequence. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-5 The altitude graph showed a slight climb before the airplane descended to 28,400 feet. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-6 The graph line indicated a slow recovery to 29,000 feet with no oscillations. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-7 The elapsed time between the first altitude excursion to recovered cruise flight was approximately 75 seconds. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-8 Of the 155 passengers on board, one passenger received serious injuries and 67 received minor injuries. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-9 The flight was scheduled for Flight Level 330 to Flight Level 370. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-10 Therefore, no information concerning forecast turbulence at Flight Level 290 was available to the flight crew. 
ntsb3702txt-1-5-5-0-11 The High Level Significant Weather Prognosis chart for that period revealed that no significant weather was shown in the area where the turbulence was encountered. 
